spencerrascoff









NOV 16, 2016
OpenTable's Christa Quarles: Embrace Radical Candor

Play 









About this episode’s guest:

CEO of OpenTable, which was founded nearly 20 years ago
Previously CFO of Playdom, which was acquired by Disney in 2010
Left “armchair quarterbacking” on Wall Street for the gaming industry

Topics covered in this episode:

Broadening the scope of possibilities through technology
Balancing a simultaneously mature and entrepreneurial environment
Being an innovator in a traditional industry

Press Play to hear the full conversation or check out the transcript below. You can also subscribe to Office Hours on iTunes and Google Play.

Rascoff: Thanks Christa for doing this.
Quarles: Thanks for having me.
Rascoff: So you had this really fascinating career on Wall Street. I think 10 years on Wall Street, right, and then moved into gaming at Playdom, which sold to Disney, and then of course you were an exec at Disney, and then Next Door. And then you got this call probably a little more than a year ago and the call to become a first-time CEO, a CEO of this amazing company and product which I love, OpenTable. So the question is what was it like the night – that night before, the night before it got announced, the night before you were presented to your new employees? What were you thinking about? What were you nervous about? What was going through your head?
Quarles: Well, I had a little bit of an interim step in there. So I joined OpenTable as the CFO, knowing that the CEO succession path was in there, but the day I got the call for the interim CEO job was a little interesting because we had talked about succession. But I was thinking a year or two, not three months, and so that was the first interesting call that I got. And as my yoga instructor says, “What’s the alternative to breathing?” And so we had a little bit of time in the interim chair, but I think becoming officially in the role and then really driving the organization forward, I think OpenTable’s an amazing company and really being in position to take it to that next level of growth, that next set of opportunities in front of it. I’m very lucky that I got to benefit from all those years behind me where there’s a two-sided marketplace. It was scaled, but there was all these opportunities that were still in front of it and really take it from here to there.
Rascoff: Did you have establish your bonafides with the product people, with engineers, designers, PMs, etc., who thought of you as a finance person, a CFO, not a product person?
Quarles: Yeah and it was a little bit of  baptism by fire because I ended up taking on the head of product role, about 28 days after I started so I just kind of –
Rascoff: While you were still CFO or when you became CEO?
Quarles: CEO, yeah, CEO. So I decided to make some changes in the organization and so I took on the head of product role. So actually at that time, I was still CFO, CEO, and head of product. Nothing like a challenge and thankfully the background in gaming was extraordinarily helpful because it’s like product development on crack because you’re constantly – I think when I was at Disney and Playdom, we probably launched 40 or 50 products at that point and had gone through the rapid iteration cycle, something that succeeded, and something that failed. So it was both lots and lots of product failure and lots of product success, but then lots of product launches. And so I had just so many iterations and so the beauty of gaming being a hit driven industry is that there’s lots of failure to teach you.
Rascoff: And so OpenTable is, by internet standards, ancient, right?
Quarles: Yes.
Rascoff: I think it was started in 1998, in the early days of the internet ,and so it’s quite different than a traditional startup in that sense, in the sense that the product is more mature. It’s been more fully built out, but you have a vision for where it’s going to go. So describe what will OpenTable be like in 5 or 10 years.
Quarles: Yeah, I think that’s exactly right. We were started in an era when there’s literally cabling being introduced inside the restaurant because Wi-Fi didn’t exist. The notion of a mobile phone wasn’t even on – flown certainly, but the computer in your pocket certainly not a thing. And what’s interesting is we kind of lucked out in some ways because we are the perfect marriage between technology and the physical world, so we are a very local business. We are in almost 40,000 restaurants around the world right now.
Rascoff: With really strong local network effects, right?
Quarles: Yeah and so we kind of benefitted because we really got into what I would consider the third wave of – the first wave was really all about the internet and that abstraction from location, and then it was 10 blue links on Google, and now it’s like, OK, how to mobile and that mobile world and take advantage of that. And then when I look beyond, it is thinking about a world where AI machine learning are driving things and very much creating that ultimate restaurant recommendation. For us, where does it look like in 5 years? I think first of all, we are a much more global company today even though we’re in eight countries around the world and technically have restaurants in about 75 countries. We’re still fairly well known in the United States and North America, but not as much outside the world. We’re now part of the largest travel company in the world in the form of Priceline, and we believe that we should be everywhere. We talk about the idea of a global dining passport. You wake up in Berlin, Dubai, Melbourne, and Tokyo. You should be able to have a curated mobile dining experience presented to you where you – then you can create a booking or you can go into a walk in and waitlist restaurant. That’s the other side of our opportunity, which is looking at market adjacencies, not just fine dining reservation taking, but truly broadening the aperture to look at casual opportunities as well to get a bigger chunk of our – of the dining experiences for our customers.
Rascoff: In terms of your leadership style, especially early on when you first took on the CEO role, is it different being a CEO?  Do you feel the weight of the world on your shoulders? And I know I sometimes do, so maybe I’m just trying to project here [laughs].
Quarles: Well, it’s a tightrope every day in the sense that you’re always trying to – I literally have the last member of the team coming on board in the next two weeks, over the last year that I’ve been trying to put in place. You’re always looking at do I have the right team? Are they performing where they need to? Making sure that –
Rascoff: So one of the first things you had to do was rebuild your team of directs?
Quarles: Right, exactly.
Rascoff: And you kind of rebooted the exec leadership team here.
Quarles: That’s right, and there were some great folks and – but by being 18 years old, you end up having a lot of tenure and trying to figure out what’s the right mix for where we want to go versus where we’ve been. And so just getting that team in place and always kind of surveying the landscape and saying OK, that’s good for maybe where we need right now, but where we’re going, I might need somebody else. And so that was definitely a critical component. I think that certainly the surprise is just how much every single word is held onto, deconstructed, interpreted, and I’m a really honest, candid, open person and so I kind of put – wear everything on my sleeve. And so making sure then I characterize, “Oh, this is a direction. This is just my opinion.” This is just me in the kitchen just asking, “Oh, what about this?  What about this?” And so making sure people understand where – what is really my driving motivation because I want to maintain that authenticity and those candid conversations, but I have to be clear and people need to know when it’s not an option.
Rascoff: Who’s talking? I do that a lot. I say like, this is – I’m not saying this as CEO. I’m just saying this as a user. Here’s a little product feedback. It doesn’t mean you have to go and prioritize this bug to the top of your list. It just means that I’m filing a bug. Approximately how many employees work at OpenTable?
Quarles: We’re about 1,000 employees.
Rascoff: OK, and you’re part of Priceline Group which is tens of thousands of employees.
Quarles: Sixteen thousand.
Rascoff: Sixteen thousand employees.
Quarles: I think. Somewhere in there.
Rascoff: Do most people that show up for work at OpenTable, do they feel that they work at OpenTable or they work at Priceline Group?
Quarles: They definitely feel like they work at OpenTable. The beauty of the structure of the Priceline Group is we are incredibly autonomous. We run in a very individual way. We even do our own tax and treasury, believe it or not. It’s very distributed and so – but it’s still – I come from very entrepreneurial backgrounds and so how do we make sure that we continue to make sure that the speed with which we’re operating, even inside of OpenTable, is one that is the right pace? We have to have a mix though because we have a business that’s running and growing, and then there’s some blank sheet stuff that we’re working on. And so trying to find kind of that schizophrenia between that highly frenetic entrepreneurial go, go, go, go. How do we think about this problem? It has never been done before. Let’s go tackle it with hey, deeply operational. We’re out there selling restaurants, day in, day out, and so just trying to find people who fit on one side of that schematic versus the other.
Rascoff: So the corporate parent provides a lot of capital, expertise sometimes, sort of when asked it sounds like, but not –
Quarles: And frankly, shielding from the public market. The benefit that we have is we don’t directly communicate OpenTable results to the public. It’s sort of put into categories, and so what that enables us to do, I think, is play long ball with discipline. Many companies try, many companies who are not public, all these stay private forever, stay private longer, they all tell themselves they’re playing long ball, but you don’t necessarily have discipline when you’re a private company in the way that you do as a public company, as I’m sure you fully recognize. We absolutely have discipline, but rare is the company that can have the Amazon-like freedom to just invest years at a time, but I think what the beauty of the Priceline Group is they say look, we’re going to make an investment in OpenTable, but it’s going to be done with a heck of a lot of discipline and we’re going to make bets that might pay off in a couple years.
Rascoff: And just to give listeners perspective, I think the Priceline acquisition of OpenTable was around $2.5 billion, and the market cap at Priceline is $70 billion, $60, $70, $80 billion, somewhere in that range.
Quarles: Yeah, it could be even $75.
Rascoff: So OpenTable is a very small part of Priceline Group. Therefore you can, as you say, play the long ball because you’re not going to impact the stock day to day, and so Priceline’s willing to make long-term investments in the future at OpenTable.
Quarles: Although as they point out, booking is obviously the behemoth in the group. It still matters whether I beat my numbers or not, and so it’s more around the expectation of conscious investment, but I very much have to beat the numbers. But I think it is an opportunity to say, “Hey, yeah, we’re not the largest part of the group for certain, but dining is a $3 trillion market. How do you dream really big and be in position to take on a much bigger chunk of the market than we currently are today?”
Rascoff: I’ve been a big proponent of dual-class stock, which Zillow Group has, which allows us to play long ball at Zillow Group and not worry as much about near-term stock price volatility because it’s founder controlled. But being part of a much larger entity is another hack to allow a company like OpenTable to be long-term oriented. Let’s talk about rebuilding your management team when you came in. How many people have you hired among your direct reports? How many direct reports do you have? What were you looking for as you rebuilt that team? And did you do it sort of serially, like you wanted to – you hired one and then saw how that person fit on the team, and then the next and the next, or you went for several people at once?
Quarles: There’s a couple things that I did. First of all, hiring is incredibly challenging. It’s a full time job. You’re out there always, and I think there is little known about what my ambition was for OpenTable. And so if you were just getting the call kind of blind, you were going, “Oh, OpenTable. Yeah, they went public. What happened?” And there wasn’t necessarily an understanding of where – so a lot of it was sort of internal PR and trying to just get people to recognize what the opportunity and ambition was. In terms of how you go about it, you try – I ended up trying to look for both a CFO and I split the product role into two. We had kind of a head of product overall, but the restaurant product and the consumer product are vastly different.
Rascoff: The restaurant part meaning the software that restaurants use?
Quarles: Yeah and it’s basically – it’s a B2B SaaS product with – that’s essentially part inventory management, almost like a saver, and part CRM. And so the skill set needed there really different from a traditional consumer product background. So I ended up looking for all three of those roles at the same time, which was not easy or awesome.
[Laughter]
Rascoff: How did employees handle that? They had a new CEO, and they knew there were other leadership changes coming?  Was that –?
Quarles: Again, I had all the hats so I guess that’s good and bad, and so – and then I’ve also – have a new head of HR, people and culture, as we call it here at OpenTable, starting in two weeks. And then we elevated some of our sales and our internal folks into more senior roles inside the company. There’s been a mix and shift of all of it and I think the challenge is each person you add and subtract changes the alchemy of that group. And one of the things that I really wanted to do when I first came in, I’m a very much a radical candor, as my friend Kim Scott will attest to, who wrote the book on that, but it’s – I think it was my first week taking over the team and we were talking about what we were working on for the next, I think, board meeting. And I said, “OK, now disagree with me.” And everyone was silent and so I think I’ve now created a culture where people feel very comfortable speaking up and reaching out, but it has to be a safe environment where they feel like, “Hey, I can exercise my opinion. I can disagree, but I’m not going to be impugned for doing so.” And each new person you add, you’ve got to test the chemistry of how that’s going to work and the dynamic, and it’s a little scary, I’ll say, every time you add a new person because you just never quite know. As much as the interviewing process is helpful, it never really gives you that sense of everybody at once and that’s the biggest challenge in making sure that that the norms of the groups are – the group are understood and frankly, appreciated and respected.
Rascoff: Isn’t it amazing that no matter how much technology there is in our businesses, at the end of the day, it’s still all about people, right?
Quarles: Until the machines take over, the humans – we’re an interesting lot and we don’t always behave at least visually rationally. I’m sure it’s rational underneath, but it’s hard because you’re managing people’s ambitions, and they’re bringing their family and their lives into the office every single day. And so you’re trying to make that blend work and where are they in their stage of career and how long have they been here, and all those different factors weigh in to how they’re going to – what person they’re bringing to the office that day.
Rascoff: You’ve touched on several themes that I’m pretty passionate about. The importance of encouraging dissent is something that I talk about a lot. Radical candor, we actually had one of the co-authors come and speak at our exec offsite, and the point is that you show someone that you care and then you’re radically candid with them, so that that’s the best way to provide feedback and it’s something that we preach at Zillow for sure.
You said something really interesting. You said each person that you add or subtract to that leadership team changes the chemistry, changes the alchemy of the group. Have you had situations in your career here or elsewhere where somebody perhaps was a high performer sort of on a different team and they still have the same skill set, but they don’t perform well with this other team because of the chemistry?
Quarles: Yeah, it happened actually when were at Playdom. We had a pretty well-functioning group and then we added a new leader role in that group. And I think what was challenging was it was a very different style than that person was used to operating in and had been at very large companies where sometimes the political game was more important. And it was disruptive and I saw it happening kind of in real time, and I think I want to be conscious to – the beauty of it is when you’re in the leadership role, it’s fully in your power and control to prevent that from happening. And so if you see even hints of behaviors that you don’t think are advantageous to that group functioning well, you tamp them out and you tamp them out quickly. And I think that’s that key is – the beauty of being in that role, you have the power to change the dynamics and really set the norms, but I have seen it and it can be destructive.  I think it can create side conversations inside negotiations and discussions that then people aren’t necessarily bringing their whole honest selves into the room, and I think the group decision making suffers as a result.
Rascoff: Yeah, I’ve seen situations where somebody – their chemistry with the rest of the team worked well in one particular role and they move into some other role or the team around them changes and they’re no longer successful. The other thing I’ve seen, kind of the corollary to that, is a particular management style works, that that person has, works well when the business is in a particular state. Let’s say a person oversees, three or four different parts of the business, and everything is going pretty well and so they’re managing kind of at 10,000 feet, and then one of the areas of those – of that business does not perform well and it’s time for them to go down to – into the trenches and they don’t do a good job transitioning between those two states. It’s interesting because the person’s skill set hasn’t changed. They have all the same intellect, the same energy, passion, whatever, but they were successful in one – at one point in time and they’re no longer successful at another.
Quarles: The key question I always ask in there is your work avoidance. What are the things that you hate doing in your job? And in that situation, if you’re not good at going down deep, then you better find a strategy so that you don’t have to and so you better make sure people are around you. And you make sure succession planning is thought through because if you’re put in a position where you’re having to do the part of your job that you frankly hate, you’re not going to be good at it. You’re not going to enjoy it and temporary is one thing, but if you – you better have a strategy around that. I’m always asking people what part of your job you hate. There’s always a part of your job you hate so then what are your strategies for mitigation? How do you get around that? And if those strategies fail, like somebody leaves and now they’re having to dive in, then it’s a signal to me that they’re going to have some challenges and they haven’t thought through or don’t understand frankly what those weaknesses are because it’s all about self awareness.
Rascoff: This is as another one of my management tenets is that when people aren’t doing their job effectively, it’s usually not because they don’t have the particular skill set to do that job well. It’s because of a low level of engagement because they’re not fired up about that particular role at that point in time. In theory, you’ve done a good enough job screening them for their skill set on the way in. There are exceptions obviously, but it’s more about making sure that they’re engaged in that particular role and a key way to improve engagement is to try to remove things that they don’t like doing from their job.
Let’s talk about innovation. This is a company that, again, was started in 1998 and I worry about this a lot at Zillow. We started in 2006, so we’re now in our second decade. Most tech companies lose a step in their – at the end of their first decade and they lose two or three steps in their second decade and most of them falter, and there are very few category leaders that are ten or more years old. OpenTable has benefited from its really strong network effect. You have a lot of restaurants. That gets a lot of diners. You have a lot of diners. That gets a lot of restaurants and network effects are notoriously difficult to disrupt, but that could also create a lazy environment where you’re not being forced into it because you don’t feel like you’re under constant attack. So how do you maintain innovation with a company that’s been around as long as OpenTable?
Quarles: Yeah, and I would say OpenTable did wait a little too long to modernize its overall stack for example. It was a monolithic code base up until 2012, and now a lot of that work has been done to chop it up into a service oriented architecture and we can ship every day, which was so not the case even several years ago. If you start thinking about rapid iterative AB testing culture, that was something that wasn’t even possible technically inside the organization just a handful of years ago. That has been really important to kind of transition that all, I think, but continuing to look forward and say okay, what are the new ways forward for our business?
Obviously mobile is the majority of our dining activity. Now that’s happening in those devices and what’s interesting is we’re seeing entirely different use cases appear because I know where you are. I know what’s available near you and so this whole dining within the hour is a brand new use case that didn’t even exist several years ago, before the mobile device came to be. I think the cool thing is when I do look forward and thinking about an AI driven world and where machine learning is going and how do our data science teams learn and iterate and operate, so one area is just I want to create the ultimate restaurant recommendation engine. The most frustrating thing is you go and you go like, “Oh, I want to go to restaurant X,” and it’s booked up or something, or it’s maybe not even on the OpenTable network, although there are very few restaurants that are not on OpenTable, and you should all be on OpenTable. But it’s still saying, “Oh, I know where that restaurant’s located.  I know the price point. I know the menu items. I know all this information, all this signal, and I hopefully know something about you at this point. I know what your preferences have been. I know where you’ve dined in the past. How do I create recommendations specifically for you?”
Rascoff: What about payments? How important is payments to your innovation, so being able to get up from the table at the end of a meal and have OpenTable pay?
Quarles: Yeah, we have dabbled a lot and we’ve innovated a lot in payments, and I’m on my now third iteration on the payment. I would say on payments in general, and I think anytime you look at financial innovation, you see these really slow adoption curves and then eventually it kinks up. Look at ATM adoption, even online banking adoption, and I still contend that we’re in year two of the seven year journey on mobile payments.
Rascoff: Is it harder to get the restaurants on board or the diners?
Quarles: It’s harder to get the restaurants on board and primarily because they’re wedded to a point of sale system so they have MICROS primarily in the United States and other countries, it’s a different point of sale system. And there’s just not a lot of motivation to integrate the point of sale so that’s been the challenge, and so we’ve tried a number things. We tried the full on point of sale integration just because. I think we’ve also tried to go around the point of sale system. We had a product called OpenTable Tab that we were trying to understand and see is that the right solution. We’re now looking and saying OK, is there another way to get into point of sale? Apple Pay has just hit its two year anniversary and I think still trying to make progress. I do believe though when you’ve experienced an OpenTable pay restaurant, it is magic. It is magic. You’re sitting there. You can see the items showing up in your phone, and then – and it just happened to me the other day. I had to go. I had a meeting I had to get to and I just hit the bar, slide it over, and I’m good to go, and there’s no dance at the end of the dining. People want that Uber-ization in the restaurant experience. They want to not be wed to – but its how do I get all the infrastructure in place to actually get it accomplished?  We’re looking at how do we do that and we’re making progress, but I always wish it was faster.
Rascoff: It’s interesting. When I asked about innovation, you immediately went to the importance of making sure that the technology is service-oriented, allows for rapid iteration, and it sounds like you probably went through a big re-architecture to enable that. Did you find other parts of the organization, like HR, PR, social media, consumer marketing, finance even, all of the sudden became more innovative when they saw a product team that was able to ship code daily, weekly, instead of every quarter or two and there was more product innovation happening for the consumer, now all of the sudden these other nontechnical parts of the organization started being more innovative?
Quarles: Well, and I think it goes into just the – and the importance of data, frankly, and it’s that line. If you have data, bring the data. If we’re using opinion, let’s use mine. I’ve encouraged every single department here to know your data and so if you’re in HR, you should know who are the employees. Where are they going? What’s the retention rate of our employees? If it’s in finance, you better know your numbers and data, but just across the board and how data plays into this role of we – our PM sounds like, “We don’t know if it’s going to work.:” Obviously, I have a point of view, but we’re often surprised and so being in position to let the data help show you the way. How do you steer the whole company to getting and receiving, analyzing, and knowing their data? When I’m in a meeting and I ask a fairly simple question, I think, and somebody can’t get the answer quickly, it’s a bad sign for me. It’s like, uh-oh, they don’t know their business. They don’t know their data. And then I ask, “Well, why can’t you? Is it hard to get? Are we not looking at those?” One of the things I’m trying to do is we were all about the reservation and we spent very little time thinking about what happened before the reservation. All the tagging of activity of just user behavior prior to a reservation hadn’t really been focused on and so we weren’t even collecting the data in some instances. So how were we going to help drive discovery when we don’t even know what’s happening prior to the reservation? Getting a whole lot more kind of on people to kind of understand what those pre-conditions are to what ultimately makes us money here, which is that connection between the restaurant and the diner.
Rascoff: Is there anything you would have done differently thinking now back on your first year as CEO? If you knew then what you know now, anything that you would have changed?
Quarles: I don’t know if I would have taken on so many jobs at once, frankly. It was not good for my sleep or gray hair, to be honest. It was hard on me and so I might have been measured, and part of it is when I feel like it’s not going to work, I just end it.  I don’t prolong. I don’t wait. I just say, “Hey, this isn’t going to work for your or us,” and so moving quickly on those, I don’t really regret it. It’s just it’s personally painful sometimes.
Rascoff: It took a toll, right. OK, well, congratulations.  I use OpenTable probably two or three times a week.
Quarles: We love you.
Rascoff:  I look forward to the day when I can use payments at the end of every meal because you’re right, it is magic when you can do that. And congratulations and I should add for listeners that your GlassDoor CEO approval rating is awesome. I think even higher than mine so that’s – it was a point of pride for me and now there’s a little friendly competition between me and you on our GlassDoor ratings. Anyway, thanks a lot. Congratulations.
Quarles: Thanks so much, Spencer.
















